Organization Description
The Walt L. Shamel Community Garden started as a pair of vacant lots on Dean Street in the mid-1980s and was transformed by neighbors into a
thriving garden and community space. Now we need your help to ensure that the garden continues to flourish!
Hours: Regular open garden hours are Saturdays and Sundays during the growing
season (April 1-October 31), and will be clearly posted on the front gate. Members
may access the garden at any time.
Organization Leadership
The garden is broken down into volunteer committees ,and then decide things collectively at meetings. Compost Committee: responsible for
managing garden compost throughout the year, and coordinating compost services for the public. Chicken Committee: responsible for chicken
care, including coordinating daily shifts, coop cleaning, hay and feed ordering duties, among others. Annual Halloween block party/parade
Committee: responsible to coordinate the annual Halloween block party, including communications, decorations, cooking and cleaning, and
obtaining street closure permit (if required). Executive Committee: responsible for administration and garden leadership, includes the four officers
and garden coordinator.
Allstar executive staff that are essential to the Walt L. Shamel garden organization are the follows.
- Gregory Anderson, Green Thumb Outreach Coordinator,
- Deborah Edwards-Anderson, Chicken Committee
- Cody Israel, President
- Rodney Duncan, Event Committee
History with NYC Open Spaces
During COVID, our compost operation has struggled to keep pace with increased demand from the community. In addition, costs associated with
our chicken flock, port a potty, and necessary maintenance of the garden have outstripped our membership dues. Composting... Community...
Chickens! Whatever the garden does for you, please give what you can to support it.
Tax-exempt Status
We are a volunteer group that would like to request one-time fiscal sponsorship from Partnerships for Parks through City Parks Foundation.

Proposal Name
Renovate The Natural Bioswale
Programming Areas
Environmental Action, Health and Wellness, Live Arts and Culture
Please respond to each prompt to the best of your abilities.
Proposal Overview
The proposal is to renovate the natural bioswale in the garden with the intent to beautify Crown Heights, promoting biodiversity, and
strengthening community bonds. Supporting native pollinators helps maintain local biodiversity, supporting ecosystem health, and contributes to
the overall well-being of the community. One of the primary needs we aim to address through this proposal is the improvement and beautification
of the natural bioswale in the garden. Bioswales are crucial components of urban stormwater management systems that help filter and absorb
rainwater, reducing runoff and improving water quality. However, over time, the bioswale in the garden has become neglected and requires
renovation to restore its functionality and aesthetic appeal.
Community Engagement
The garden community that our organization intends to serve with this proposal is Crown Heights and the surrounding area in Dean St Block in
Brooklyn. Crown Heights is a diverse and vibrant community of individuals from various ethnic and cultural backgrounds. It is home to families,
young professionals, and long-time residents who will be thrilled and invested in the beautification of their neighborhood. This garden is uniquely
positioned to meet those needs since it is a green oasis in a heavily dense urban environment. As well as with the local school attending offering
opportunities for environmental education and raising awareness about the importance of nature and ecological conservation. Lastly this green
space often serve as gathering places for residents, fostering a sense of community and social interaction.
Goals & Measurable Outcomes
The project aims to enhance the aesthetic appeal of the garden surrounding the bioswale, creating an attractive and inviting space for community
members. This includes selecting and planting native vegetation, adding decorative elements, and improving overall landscaping design.
Measuring the results can be done by monitoring plant growth, assessing plant health indicators (e.g., leaf color, pest/disease presence), and
tracking the establishment of new vegetation. Regular observations and documentation will provide insights into the garden's progress and overall
viability. Measuring community engagement is crucial to understand the project's impact on community involvement and awareness. This can be
done by tracking the number of participants in educational workshops, community meetings, or volunteer events related to the garden renovation.
Measuring the garden's utilization by community members can indicate the success of the beautification efforts.

Funding Need
The current state of our organization's budget reflects the financial resources available for our operations, projects, and initiatives. As of the latest
update, we have diligently managed our budget to ensure prudent financial practices. However, like any organization, we face ongoing challenges
in meeting our ambitious goals to create a positive impact in our community and the environment. In conclusion, securing funding support from
the NYC Green Fund is an immediate financial need for our organization. It will not only help us accelerate our impact but also enable us to
engage with the community, foster innovation, and align with the city's environmental priorities effectively. We are committed to utilizing the
funds responsibly and transparently to create a greener and more sustainable future for our community and beyond.
